njan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Balderston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places in Lancashire called Balderston(e), deriving their names from the genitive case of the Old English personal name <i>Baldhere</i> (composed of the elements <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’ + <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","Scottish: habitational name from Balderston in West Lothian, which has the same etymology as 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Balderson","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and Northamptonshire): assimilated form of   Balderston  , rather than a patronymic from <i>Balder</i>, appearances to the contrary notwithstanding."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Balderston was born in 1239, in Blackburn, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Balderston, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Richard Balderston, was 28. He married Mrs. William De Balderston about 1269, in Blackburn, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1292, in Baildon, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1239–1292":"1239–1292","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1294–Female":"1294–Surnud","1208–1266":"1208–1266","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","1239":"1239","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1332":"1332","1243":"1243","ABT 1269":"umbes 1269","ABT 1238":"umbes 1238","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1208":"1208","Baildon, Yorkshire, England":"Baildon, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<Osbaldeston, Blackburn, Lancashire, England>":"Blackburn, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Blackburn, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1239–1292":"1239–1292","1243–Female":"1243–Kuollut","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1294–Female":"1294–Kuollut","1208–1266":"1208–1266","1212–Female":"1212–Kuollut","1239":"1239","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1332":"1332","1243":"1243","ABT 1269":"noin 1269","ABT 1238":"noin 1238","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1208":"1208","Baildon, Yorkshire, England":"Baildon, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","<Osbaldeston, Blackburn, Lancashire, England>":"Blackburn, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Blackburn, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1239–1292":"1239–1292","1243–Female":"1243–Décédée","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1294–Female":"1294–Décédée","1208–1266":"1208–1266","1212–Female":"1212–Décédée","1239":"1239","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1332":"1332","1243":"1243","ABT 1269":"environ 1269","ABT 1238":"environ 1238","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1208":"1208","Baildon, Yorkshire, England":"Baildon, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","<Osbaldeston, Blackburn, Lancashire, England>":"Blackburn, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Blackburn